1
00:00:01,246 --> 00:00:27,894
Namo tassa bhagavato arahato sama sambuddhasa Namo tassa bhagavato arahato sama sambuddhasa Namo tassa bhagavato arahato sama sambuddhasa

2
00:00:28,161 --> 00:00:32,548
Homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble and fully self-enlightened one.

3
00:00:34,371 --> 00:00:40,118
So, I'm going to start on this new chapter, which is entitled The Bringer of Light.

4
00:00:41,020 --> 00:00:43,543
So again, it's from the Buddha's words by Bhikkhu Bodhi.

5
00:00:44,424 --> 00:00:48,951
And I just want to start by quoting something from his foreword.

6
00:00:50,914 --> 00:00:55,299
So, when...

7
00:00:57,557 --> 00:01:08,272
When Buddhism first came to the West, they thought that the Buddha was really the sun god, a mythical figure.

8
00:01:08,694 --> 00:01:25,658
It was only later that, when they rediscovered the sites in India, I think it was Cunningham, who was an army surveyor, found the actual sites and therefore established the truth that in fact he was...

9
00:01:25,638 --> 00:01:31,489
a human being, lived about 500 years before the common era.

10
00:01:34,013 --> 00:01:36,939
At the same time was the Jain leader, see, the Nagantha.

11
00:01:38,001 --> 00:01:48,421
And at the same time that the scriptures were being developed in the Brahminical religion, which we now call Hinduism.

12
00:01:49,921 --> 00:01:53,864
So we'll go into a little bit of that later on.

13
00:01:54,424 --> 00:02:16,366
But it says here, you see, depending on our biases and predispositions, we may choose to regard the Buddha as a liberal ethical reformer of a degenerate Brahmanism, as a great secular humanist, as a radical empiricist, as an existential psychologist,

14
00:02:16,685 --> 00:02:25,513
as a proponent of a sweeping agnosticism, or as a precursor of any intellectual faction that meets our fancy.

15
00:02:26,793 --> 00:02:35,842
So whenever Buddhism has gone into a different country, it's always been reinterpreted by that country.

16
00:02:36,743 --> 00:02:39,586
And it's always kept the basic tenets.

17
00:02:40,627 --> 00:02:47,596
Nobody can declare Buddhism without the Four Noble Truths.

18
00:02:47,695 --> 00:02:49,897
I mean, it's just absolutely basic.

19
00:02:49,877 --> 00:02:54,965
But the way that a country receives it depends on their tradition they receive.

20
00:02:55,284 --> 00:03:00,893
So, for instance, in Tibet, the shamanism of Bon had a great effect on it.

21
00:03:01,813 --> 00:03:09,944
And then when it moved to China, Taoism had a great effect on the reinterpretation of the Buddhist teachings.

22
00:03:10,381 --> 00:03:12,864
When it got to Japan, it was similar.

23
00:03:13,985 --> 00:03:18,512
The Japanese had a similar problem with things like rebirth, because they didn't have it.

24
00:03:19,212 --> 00:03:24,860
They had ancestors and they worshipped, but they didn't have this idea of onward-going rebirthing.

25
00:03:24,881 --> 00:03:31,389
And their way of tackling that problem was to simply centre the teaching on the immediate presence.

26
00:03:31,409 --> 00:03:38,379
So whenever you read Buddhism, it's all about the here and now, rather than these future lives, which you would get from the scriptures, you see.

27
00:03:39,895 --> 00:03:46,169
When it comes to the West, what's happened in the West is that a whole load of stuff has come.

28
00:03:46,389 --> 00:03:50,799
All types of Buddhism have landed on a doorstep.

29
00:03:50,818 --> 00:03:54,066
From every country where there is Buddhism, it's here.

30
00:03:54,205 --> 00:03:57,312
It's here in Britain, it's here in Europe, it's definitely here in America.

31
00:03:57,681 --> 00:04:02,769
So as it comes in, we ourselves have our own interpretation.

32
00:04:03,109 --> 00:04:07,314
Not only as a society as a whole, but individually, you see.

33
00:04:07,814 --> 00:04:09,137
It depends where you come from.

34
00:04:09,657 --> 00:04:15,185
So here we have a sort of list of ways that people have seen the Buddha.

35
00:04:15,906 --> 00:04:24,297
Often he attracts people who believe in only one life.

36
00:04:24,648 --> 00:04:33,706
who are based in science because the way the Buddha talks about the psychology is so close to the way we understand it.

37
00:04:34,226 --> 00:04:38,295
And that's one of the reasons why all this mindfulness has entered into the mainstream.

38
00:04:38,976 --> 00:04:43,204
It's because we can understand it, we can understand the human being from that point of view.

39
00:04:43,245 --> 00:04:46,250
It's almost basic psychology.

40
00:04:46,230 --> 00:04:56,004
and the role of desire addiction all that sort of stuff so it makes it makes sort of immediate sense to us that that part of the buddha's teaching you see

41
00:04:56,254 --> 00:04:57,757
He's an empiricist.

42
00:04:57,776 --> 00:05:03,444
In other words, nothing is given to us without it being tried out.

43
00:05:03,625 --> 00:05:06,870
If it doesn't work, it isn't Buddhism, full stop.

44
00:05:07,391 --> 00:05:15,521
So everything that he puts to us through the meditational practices, which isn't just this vipassana, it includes the goodwill practice and all.

45
00:05:15,963 --> 00:05:17,685
There's a whole flurry of practices.

46
00:05:18,545 --> 00:05:21,771
And they're there as something for us to try.

47
00:05:22,190 --> 00:05:24,894
It has to be something experienced.

48
00:05:24,875 --> 00:05:26,557
And it either works for us or it doesn't.

49
00:05:29,141 --> 00:05:40,358
I mean, one of the things that annihilationists in his day, materialists, would say to the Buddha, you know, like, I don't believe in all this rebirth stuff.

50
00:05:40,377 --> 00:05:46,507
He said, but even so, if you follow the Dharma, if you follow these teachings, you'll get benefits in this life, you know.

51
00:05:47,327 --> 00:05:53,396
And if after this life you're just annihilated, fine, but at least you'll have the benefit of it in this life, you see.

52
00:05:55,064 --> 00:06:00,511
And then existential psychologist.

53
00:06:01,091 --> 00:06:12,125
So it's just a psychology for this present moment with nothing beyond really the psychophysical organism.

54
00:06:13,266 --> 00:06:17,350
It's like defining a human being only by their body and their minds.

55
00:06:17,490 --> 00:06:21,696
Their mind meaning their emotional life and their thoughts.

56
00:06:22,182 --> 00:06:26,187
And then a sweeping agnosticism, like not believing in anything.

57
00:06:26,949 --> 00:06:39,589
This often refers to a discourse where he goes to these people called the Kalamas, and we'll come to that later on in the book, who are very confused because this teacher says this, this teacher turns up and says that, so they're completely confused.

58
00:06:40,170 --> 00:06:43,295
And by the end of this talking to them, he says, look...

59
00:06:43,714 --> 00:06:45,858
If it's not right for you, it's not true.

60
00:06:46,117 --> 00:06:47,180
You've got to try it out.

61
00:06:47,439 --> 00:06:49,362
You've got to actually make it true for yourself.

62
00:06:50,845 --> 00:07:01,199
So in a sense, it's that sort of not believing anything, not believing anything in the sense of a blind belief.

63
00:07:01,653 --> 00:07:03,535
It's more in the sense of a confidence.

64
00:07:04,156 --> 00:07:18,274
So we have this quality of saddha, which is translated as confidence, not so much faith, because if you say faith to people, it tends to give the suggestion that you've got to believe it, whether it's true or not.

65
00:07:18,975 --> 00:07:20,437
But that would be the wrong attitude.

66
00:07:21,098 --> 00:07:25,264
From the Buddha's point of view, that would actually undermine your investigation.

67
00:07:25,901 --> 00:07:30,793
And it's the process of investigating ourselves which is the process of liberation.

68
00:07:31,334 --> 00:07:33,738
So if you don't investigate yourself you just stay as you are.

69
00:07:35,463 --> 00:07:40,754
You can read as many books as you want which is not going to liberate you from suffering you see.

70
00:07:41,713 --> 00:07:59,975
So that's the first thing, you see, that basically we have to, you know, we have to remember that when we read about the Buddha himself, the Buddha as a person, etc., we're always interpreting what he does from what satisfies us, you see.

71
00:07:59,956 --> 00:08:14,577
But, unfortunately for a lot of people, the Buddha doesn't talk to himself, talk about himself in quite such humanistic terms, in terms of, you know, I am just this body and mind, and all that.

72
00:08:14,918 --> 00:08:17,961
He actually refers to himself as the Tathāgata.

73
00:08:18,644 --> 00:08:27,836
Now this word is, the word that it is, is Tathā, which means there, right?

74
00:08:28,204 --> 00:08:34,446
And it can be either translated as come there, Agatha, or gone there.

75
00:08:34,466 --> 00:08:37,876
And basically it translates as transcendent.

76
00:08:37,957 --> 00:08:42,664
It's somebody who has transcended the psychophysical organism.

77
00:08:42,764 --> 00:08:45,168
Now that's a very different sort of statement, you see.

78
00:08:45,830 --> 00:09:00,152
And in that sense, he's fulfilling, in his own terms, some very deep, original archetype that is within us, that there is something in us which is actually beyond this body and mind.

79
00:09:01,110 --> 00:09:01,772
Right?

80
00:09:01,792 --> 00:09:12,605
So, depending on where you stand, you see, that would either be an impossibility, and you're not prepared to accept it, or it opens up a possibility.

81
00:09:13,366 --> 00:09:15,009
I had a person come there.

82
00:09:15,249 --> 00:09:18,813
He was studying, I think it was some sort of science.

83
00:09:18,874 --> 00:09:21,236
It might have been biology at a university.

84
00:09:21,256 --> 00:09:30,408
And he came on one of the courses I was holding at Gaia House, and he came to me after two or three days when I'd given these talks, and he said...

85
00:09:31,029 --> 00:09:32,974
He said, I came here to meditate.

86
00:09:33,615 --> 00:09:36,980
I don't believe all this stuff about afterlife and all this stuff.

87
00:09:37,000 --> 00:09:37,903
And he couldn't handle it.

88
00:09:37,962 --> 00:09:38,383
Off he went.

89
00:09:39,666 --> 00:09:48,481
So, you know, it's like, I wasn't, I would never put it to him that he has to believe this in order to get the benefit of the meditation.

90
00:09:48,749 --> 00:09:55,828
But he just couldn't handle being in any situation that suggested that there was anything beyond this body and mind.

91
00:09:57,714 --> 00:10:01,323
The human being as you can actually see them.

92
00:10:01,995 --> 00:10:12,490
This idea of something beyond, you see, all over the scriptures, the explanation of Nibbana is always something beyond the phenomenal.

93
00:10:12,610 --> 00:10:13,511
It's an island.

94
00:10:14,072 --> 00:10:19,580
It's something which is separated from, that you have to move towards, you see.

95
00:10:20,000 --> 00:10:23,024
So that's there within the scriptures, you see.

96
00:10:23,004 --> 00:10:31,394
But again, you have to remember that that's not something you have to believe, but it's something we need to know.

97
00:10:31,433 --> 00:10:43,126
That he doesn't talk about himself as just being a liver and heart and a bit of emotions and the brain.

98
00:10:51,135 --> 00:10:52,977
And the one that I think...

99
00:10:53,649 --> 00:10:58,256
Where we associate with the Buddha is, of course, with his humanness.

100
00:10:58,277 --> 00:11:00,880
So he goes through that struggle.

101
00:11:01,062 --> 00:11:05,889
He actually liberates himself as a human being here on this earth.

102
00:11:06,649 --> 00:11:12,840
And the path that he treads is the path that he's actually pointing to.

103
00:11:12,820 --> 00:11:18,131
And he says that he's not inventing the path, he's discovering it, he's rediscovering it.

104
00:11:18,552 --> 00:11:25,129
It was always there, it's just that he was able to rediscover it and lay it out before us.

105
00:11:26,532 --> 00:11:31,403
So it's not that he invented Buddhism.

106
00:11:33,187 --> 00:11:50,437
And that's what I think to us as Westerners, that's where we make our connection to him as somebody who also practiced, who also went through all the problems that we have and then declared that he didn't have those problems anymore.

107
00:11:58,264 --> 00:12:04,835
And of course included in this business of things that we find hard to believe is the whole teaching around rebirth.

108
00:12:06,076 --> 00:12:15,089
And we'll come to passages which presume that that's exactly what happens to us.

109
00:12:15,610 --> 00:12:20,998
Now, I've put on my website, if you go onto it, on the front page...

110
00:12:21,197 --> 00:12:24,945
on the left panel there, there's... what do I call it?

111
00:12:25,886 --> 00:12:26,368
Oh dear.

112
00:12:28,211 --> 00:12:29,212
It's a special page.

113
00:12:32,019 --> 00:12:36,287
No, I've named this... a periodical...

114
00:12:36,267 --> 00:12:37,089
Subjects.

115
00:12:37,229 --> 00:12:38,230
Something like that.

116
00:12:38,250 --> 00:12:44,203
And if you click on that, it'll take you to a page which looks at certain things that we have difficulties with.

117
00:12:44,283 --> 00:12:50,597
So rebirth, euthanasia, vegetarianism, brain.

118
00:12:51,399 --> 00:12:52,782
No, not so much that.

119
00:12:52,802 --> 00:12:55,508
It's more in the sense of things that...

120
00:12:55,488 --> 00:13:05,783
We have, well, those three things, euthanasia, vegetarianism, things like that.

121
00:13:06,565 --> 00:13:18,602
And there's a link there to a YouTube of a young American boy who remembers his past life as a pilot being shot down by the Japanese in the Pacific.

122
00:13:19,082 --> 00:13:24,971
And if you follow that through, you see him both as a little kid, about four years old, and later on as an 11-year-old.

123
00:13:25,626 --> 00:13:29,533
And there's no doubt that he...

124
00:13:29,552 --> 00:13:33,317
I mean, it's astonishing because he knows things about the family.

125
00:13:33,618 --> 00:13:36,702
He doesn't belong to his old family.

126
00:13:38,125 --> 00:13:39,166
But he remembers them.

127
00:13:39,567 --> 00:13:40,408
He remembers who it is.

128
00:13:40,488 --> 00:13:47,758
And when he goes to see his sister, who then is an elderly lady, he tells her things that only the family would know.

129
00:13:48,960 --> 00:13:52,404
So you've got a big problem if you think it's something that comes through on your genes.

130
00:13:52,825 --> 00:13:54,687
Because he's come from a completely different...

131
00:13:55,546 --> 00:14:17,908
gene family see so anyway i i'm going on a bit so i just want to read this opening passage which actually is the buddha declaring himself as to who he is and what he is you see and uh well we'll read it first so monks so remember when we say monks it's anybody who's listening yeah

132
00:14:18,461 --> 00:14:32,826
There is one person who arises in the world for the welfare of the multitude, for the happiness of the multitude, out of compassion for the world, for the good, welfare and happiness of devas and humans, devas of gods.

133
00:14:32,846 --> 00:14:34,009
Who is that one person?

134
00:14:34,350 --> 00:14:37,755
It is the Tathagata, the Arahant, the perfectly enlightened one.

135
00:14:38,096 --> 00:14:40,200
This is that one person.

136
00:14:40,179 --> 00:14:43,184
Now, you'll notice here he says, for the multitude.

137
00:14:43,264 --> 00:14:45,327
Often that's translated as the many.

138
00:14:46,089 --> 00:14:48,212
He doesn't say for everybody.

139
00:14:49,153 --> 00:14:51,618
Some people just aren't ready for it.

140
00:14:51,638 --> 00:14:54,001
And this word compassion is a lovely word.

141
00:14:54,142 --> 00:14:57,547
It's not the usual word that some of you might know, karuna.

142
00:14:57,908 --> 00:14:59,370
It's anukampana.

143
00:14:59,350 --> 00:15:03,556
And Kampati means to shake, to tremble.

144
00:15:04,096 --> 00:15:08,363
And Anu means to tremble towards.

145
00:15:08,903 --> 00:15:20,380
So you get the feeling of a resonance, out of resonance with other human beings, he offers this teaching to alleviate their suffering.

146
00:15:20,400 --> 00:15:28,513
There is one person arising in the world who is unique without a peer, without counterpart, incomparable, unequaled, matchless,

147
00:15:28,696 --> 00:15:30,460
unrivaled, the best of humans.

148
00:15:30,799 --> 00:15:31,922
Who is that one person?

149
00:15:32,363 --> 00:15:35,710
It is the Tathagata, the Arahant, the perfectly enlightened one.

150
00:15:36,191 --> 00:15:37,494
This is that one person.

151
00:15:37,995 --> 00:15:41,301
Now it sounds really sure enough, doesn't it?

152
00:15:41,321 --> 00:15:44,167
I mean, can you imagine saying something like that about yourself?

153
00:15:44,226 --> 00:15:45,168
I am the one.

154
00:15:46,769 --> 00:15:54,136
So here we have to recognise that these scriptures were worked on and there are three levels to the scriptures.

155
00:15:54,256 --> 00:16:07,029
The original level you can see, it's very chatty, it's very conversational and you can see that his teaching has not been formalised so greatly as it becomes.

156
00:16:07,711 --> 00:16:12,456
Then there's the middle section which is the formalised part and this would be part of that.

157
00:16:12,436 --> 00:16:23,010
And then towards the end of the scriptures, you get these lists, you get sort of lists which move then into a later work, which is called the Abhidhamma, you see.

158
00:16:24,013 --> 00:16:30,621
And he obviously said things about himself, which were then, you know, built up into these statements.

159
00:16:32,625 --> 00:16:33,826
And we'll come back to that too.

160
00:16:34,707 --> 00:16:39,355
The manifestation of one person is the manifestation of great love.

161
00:16:39,908 --> 00:16:43,072
of great vision, of great light, of great radiance.

162
00:16:43,693 --> 00:16:54,472
It is the manifestation of the six things unsurpassed, the realization of the four analytical knowledges, the penetration of the various elements, of the diversity of elements.

163
00:16:55,134 --> 00:17:03,368
It is the realization of the fruit of knowledge and liberation, the realization of the fruits of stream entry, once returning from

164
00:17:03,634 --> 00:17:05,558
non-returning and Arahatship.

165
00:17:06,039 --> 00:17:07,142
Who is that one person?

166
00:17:07,542 --> 00:17:10,650
It is the Tathagata, the Arahant, the perfectly enlightened one.

167
00:17:10,950 --> 00:17:12,232
This is that one person.

168
00:17:13,015 --> 00:17:19,708
Now there's a hell of a lot in that little paragraph because it presumes that we understand all these different things that they're talking about.

169
00:17:20,509 --> 00:17:22,875
But what he's saying here is that

170
00:17:23,647 --> 00:17:29,076
He has discovered this path, and he's not only discovered it, he knows it root and branch.

171
00:17:29,978 --> 00:17:35,027
And he's been able to lay down all the facets of that particular path.

172
00:17:35,567 --> 00:17:42,338
And you can see that from the massive amount of teaching that there is around these scriptures.

173
00:17:43,019 --> 00:17:47,326
So that every part of that journey is covered.

174
00:17:47,611 --> 00:17:49,474
And that's what he's saying here.

175
00:17:50,758 --> 00:17:52,461
We can go into the stuff.

176
00:17:52,863 --> 00:17:56,411
This stuff comes up later, so we needn't go into it in such great detail.

177
00:17:56,731 --> 00:18:03,949
But just so that the six things that are unsurpassed is the unsurpassed sight of the Buddha and his disciples.

178
00:18:04,282 --> 00:18:08,230
The unsurpassed hearing of the Dharma from the Buddha and his disciples.

179
00:18:08,911 --> 00:18:13,898
The unsurpassed gain, the gain of confidence in the Buddha and his disciples.

180
00:18:14,400 --> 00:18:15,863
The unsurpassed training.

181
00:18:16,123 --> 00:18:23,035
So this is, you see, the higher morality, higher mind, higher wisdom as taught by the Buddha and his disciples.

182
00:18:23,015 --> 00:18:29,601
The unsurpassed service, the service to the Buddha and his disciples, and the unsurpassed recollection.

183
00:18:30,001 --> 00:18:34,925
So that's meditating, contemplating the Buddha and his disciples.

184
00:18:34,945 --> 00:18:36,627
These are the six unsurpassable things.

185
00:18:37,308 --> 00:18:48,538
When it comes to the analytical knowledges, the four analytical knowledges, it's basically a way of discussing things, a logical way, a philosophical way.

186
00:18:49,640 --> 00:18:52,583
And they include an analysis of a meaning of something,

187
00:18:52,563 --> 00:19:07,200
the reasons and causes and conditions why they arise, an analysis of the language that you're actually using, and sort of understanding all the processes that bring about something.

188
00:19:07,519 --> 00:19:08,621
It's an analysis of that.

189
00:19:08,862 --> 00:19:17,912
So the Buddha's teaching is really about deconstructing things, about analyzing things and seeing how they come to be.

190
00:19:18,887 --> 00:19:26,886
And then finally, all that business about the elements, all that is to do with what makes up a human being.

191
00:19:27,107 --> 00:19:31,980
Again, there'll be another time we can go into that in more detail.

192
00:19:32,761 --> 00:19:36,711
I mean, obviously, the first two big elements are the body and the mind.

193
00:19:37,702 --> 00:19:48,513
And then these things that we mentioned at the end, the stream entry, once returning, non-returning, and Arahash, these are the four paths and fruits that are entered upon on the path.

194
00:19:48,614 --> 00:19:53,638
And they are gradations of insight as you go through, you see.

195
00:19:54,019 --> 00:20:00,486
And they each have an effect on our personality and on our characters, you see.

196
00:20:00,506 --> 00:20:07,153
So, for instance, by the time that you're a non-returner, you've lost, really...

197
00:20:07,133 --> 00:20:16,924
any attachment, any psychological dependency on any pleasures of this world for your happiness.

198
00:20:17,486 --> 00:20:19,769
So your happiness is based on something else.

199
00:20:19,788 --> 00:20:20,809
That's what attachment is.

200
00:20:20,930 --> 00:20:26,856
Attachment is psychological dependency on something outside ourselves for our personal happiness.

201
00:20:28,920 --> 00:20:34,727
So that gives you some idea of how the Buddha talked about himself.

202
00:20:36,107 --> 00:21:02,378
So, although there are these interpretations, remember that it's for us, really, to decide where the Buddha stands for us in our lives, and yet not to be closed by that definition that we've put on that person, just to be open to the fact that actually what he's saying about himself may actually be true.

203
00:21:05,241 --> 00:21:05,321
See?

204
00:21:08,643 --> 00:21:09,223
Very good.

205
00:21:09,384 --> 00:21:30,141
I can only hope my words have been of some assistance and that in contemplating the Buddha's life it may bring about a certain urgency to your own spiritual practice that you may arrive to that lovely place of Nibbana sooner rather than later.

206
00:21:30,161 --> 00:21:32,945
Sadhu, sadhu, sadhu.

